"Conservative" or "bourgeois socialism" was a term used by [[Karl Marx]] and [[Friedrich Engels]] in various pieces, including in ''[[The Communist Manifesto]]''. The [[Marxism|Marxian]] view is such that the bourgeois socialist is the sustainer of the [[Marx's theory of the state#The bourgeois state|current state of bourgeois class relations]]. Opinions vary as to whether this or that bourgeois socialist intentionally is excusing the current order, but the common thread is that they are in objective fact preserving it. Rather than abolishing [[Social class|class divisions]], they wish to simply raise everyone up to be a member of the [[bourgeoisie]] to allow everyone the ability to endlessly accumulate [[Capital (economics)|capital]] without a [[working class]]. In ''The Communist Manifesto'', Marx and Engels use [[Philanthropy|philanthropists]], [[monk]]s ("temperance fanatics") and [[Reform movement|reformers]] as examples of this type of [[Socialism|socialist]] that they saw as opposed to their own aims. In expressing its views on the subject, Marx explicitly referenced [[Pierre-Joseph Proudhon]]'s ''[[The Philosophy of Misery]]'', stating the following about bourgeois socialism: {{cquote|The Socialistic bourgeois want all the advantages of modern social conditions without the struggles and dangers necessarily resulting therefrom.}}

== External links ==
* Section of [http://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1848/communist-manifesto/ch03.htm#b ''The Communist Manifesto''] dealing with bourgeois socialism.

