{{Islamism sidebar|Concepts}}
'''Post-Islamism''' is a [[neologism]] in [[political science]], the definition 
and applicability of which has led to an intellectual debate. [[Asef Bayat]] and [[Olivier Roy (professor)|Olivier Roy]] are among the main architects of the idea.{{sfn|Gómez García|2012}}

== Terminology and definition ==
The term was coined by Iranian political sociologist [[Asef Bayat]], then associate professor of sociology at [[The American University in Cairo]] in a 1996 essay published in the journal ''[[Middle East Critique]]''.{{sfn|Mojahedi|2016|page=52}}{{sfn|Badamchi|2017|page=1}}

Bayat explained it as "a condition where, following a phase of experimentation, the appeal, energy, symbols and sources of legitimacy of [[Islamism]] get exhausted, even among its once-ardent supporters. As such, post-Islamism is not anti-Islamic, but rather reflects a tendency to resecularize religion." It originally pertained only to [[Iran]], where "post-Islamism is expressed in the idea of fusion between Islam (as a personalized faith) and individual freedom and choice; and post-Islamism is associated with the values of [[democracy]] and aspects of [[modernity]]".{{sfn|Bayat|1996|page=45}} In this context, the prefix ''post-'' does not have historic connotation, but refers to the critical departure from [[Islamist]] discourse.{{sfn|Badamchi|2017|page=4}} Bayat later pointed in 2007 that post-Islamism is both a "condition" and a "[[project]]".{{sfn|Gómez García|2012}}

"[[Postmodern]] Islamism" and "[[New Age]] Islamism" are other terms interchangeably used.{{sfn|Ismail|2008|page=626}}

French politician [[Olivier Carré]] used the term in 1991 from a different perspective, to describe the period between the [[10th century|10th]] and the [[19th century|19th]] centuries, when both Shiite and Sunni Islam "separated the [[Civil–military relations|political-military]] from the religious realm, both theoretically and in practice".{{sfn|Gómez García|2012}}

== Cases ==
In [[Iran]], the [[Iranian Reformists|Reformists]]{{sfn|Fazeli|2006|page=169}}{{sfn|Badamchi|2017|page=3}} and the group known as the ''[[Council of Nationalist-Religious Activists of Iran|Melli-Mazhabi]]'' (who are ideologically close to the [[Freedom Movement of Iran|Freedom Movement]]){{sfn|Shahibzadeh|2016|page=103}} are described as post-Islamists.

The advent of moderate parties [[Al-Wasat Party]] in [[Egypt]], as well as [[Justice and Development Party (Morocco)|Justice and Development Party]] in [[Morocco]] appeared to resemble emergance of post-Islamism, however scholars rejected that they qualify as such.{{sfn|Stacher|2002|page=432}}{{sfn|Lauzi`ere|2005|page=242}} A similar characterization applies to the [[Malaysian Islamic Party (PAS)]].{{sfn|Muller|2013}}

A 2008 [[Lowy Institute for International Policy]] paper suggests that [[Prosperous Justice Party]] of [[Indonesia]] and [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP) of [[Turkey]] are post-Islamist.{{sfn|Bubalo|Fealy|Mason|2002|page=51, 76}} According to Ahmet T. Kuru and [[Alfred Stepan]] (2012), many analysts consider Turkish AKP an example of post-Islamism, similar to [[Christian democracy|Christian democratic]] parties, but Islamic.{{sfn|Kuru|Stepan|2012|page=172}} However, some scholars such as [[Bassam Tibi]] dispute this.{{sfn|Hale|Ozbudun|2009|page=148}} İhsan Yılmaz argues that the party's ideology after 2011 is different from that of between 2001 and 2011.{{sfn|Yılmaz|2016|page=115}}

The idea has been used to describe the "ideological evolution" within the [[Ennahda Movement|Ennahda]] of [[Tunisia]].{{sfn|Cavatorta|Merone|2015}}

